  <h1>Common Product Liability Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Auden Cordell (AC), Editor-in-Chief. Contributor: Holland Devlin (HD), Recall &amp; Consumer Safety Reference. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Product liability is one of the most heavily mythologized areas of American law. Tort-reform marketing, partisan media coverage, and the bizarre cultural afterlife of the McDonald's coffee case have produced a substantial body of folk wisdom about product cases that is largely wrong. This guide walks through fifteen of the most common misconceptions and what the law actually says.</p>

  <h2>Myth 1: "The McDonald's coffee case proves the system is broken."</h2>

  <p>The Liebeck v. McDonald's case is the single most-cited example of "frivolous litigation" in American discourse. The actual facts: Stella Liebeck was a 79-year-old who suffered third-degree burns over 16% of her body when McDonald's coffee &mdash; held at 180&ndash;190&deg;F, well above the industry-standard 140&deg;F for served coffee &mdash; spilled in her lap. She required skin grafts and was hospitalized for eight days. McDonald's had received over 700 prior complaints of severe coffee burns and had paid out roughly $500,000 in prior settlements without changing the temperature. She initially asked McDonald's to cover her $20,000 in medical expenses; McDonald's refused. The jury awarded $200,000 in compensatory damages (reduced 20% for her comparative fault) and $2.7M in punitives, which the trial court reduced to $480,000. The case settled for an undisclosed amount on appeal. This is the canonical "frivolous" lawsuit. It was not frivolous; it was a strong product liability case with clear failure-to-warn and design-defect elements.</p>

  <h2>Myth 2: "Strict liability means manufacturers are automatically liable."</h2>

  <p>Strict liability is not absolute liability. The plaintiff still has to prove three elements: that the product was defective, that the defect existed when the product left the manufacturer's control, and that the defect caused the injury. The plaintiff also has to prove damages. What strict liability eliminates is the negligence element &mdash; the requirement to prove the manufacturer was careless. That is a meaningful simplification of the plaintiff's case, but it is not a free ride.</p>

  <h2>Myth 3: "If the product wasn't recalled, I don't have a case."</h2>

  <p>False. Most successful product liability cases involve products that have never been recalled. A recall is helpful evidence but not necessary. Many defective products kill or injure many people before anyone organizes a recall (or the manufacturer can be forced to recall). The absence of a recall does not mean the product is not defective.</p>

  <h2>Myth 4: "If the product was recalled, I just send it back and the manufacturer pays my medical bills."</h2>

  <p>Wrong in the opposite direction. A recall offers a refund or repair, not compensation for injury. Sending the recalled product back does not start any process of paying your medical bills or other damages; if anything, it destroys the key evidence in your personal-injury case. If you have been injured by a recalled product, do not return it &mdash; talk to a lawyer first.</p>

  <h2>Myth 5: "Federal preemption protects all FDA-approved drugs and devices from lawsuits."</h2>

  <p>Federal preemption is a doctrine with narrow application. For prescription drugs, the Supreme Court has held that state-law failure-to-warn claims are generally not preempted (Wyeth v. Levine), although generic drugs sit in a more preempted posture (PLIVA v. Mensing). For medical devices, devices approved through the FDA's premarket-approval pathway enjoy broader preemption (Riegel v. Medtronic), but devices cleared through the 510(k) pathway generally do not. Most medical devices on the market are 510(k)-cleared, not premarket-approved. The takeaway: federal preemption rarely closes the door on a state-law product claim.</p>

  <h2>Myth 6: "The statute of repose bars old cases, so my injury from a 1985 product can't be pursued."</h2>

  <p>About a third of states have a statute of repose, typically 10&ndash;15 years from original sale. Most states do not. And even in states with one, exceptions often exist for products with a longer expected useful life (heavy industrial equipment, building components) and for fraudulent concealment of the defect. Whether your case is barred depends on the specific state and the specific product. Ask a lawyer; do not assume.</p>

  <h2>Myth 7: "I bought it used, so I have no case against the manufacturer."</h2>

  <p>Used purchase does not eliminate the manufacturer's strict liability for a design or manufacturing defect. The manufacturer is liable for the defect in the product as originally sold, regardless of how many subsequent owners the product has had. Used purchase complicates the case in two ways: it raises the alteration/wear defense (the defect may not be original) and it may eliminate retailer liability (a casual private sale is not in the chain of distribution). But the manufacturer remains a defendant.</p>

  <h2>Myth 8: "If I was using the product wrong, I have no case."</h2>

  <p>The legal standard is "reasonably foreseeable use," not "intended use." Standing on a chair to change a light bulb is foreseeable misuse of a chair, and a chair must be designed (and warned about) to account for foreseeable misuse. The defense wins only when the misuse is genuinely unforeseeable and the sole proximate cause of the injury. Most "user error" claims by the defendant fail because the use was foreseeable.</p>

  <h2>Myth 9: "Class actions get the manufacturer to pay, and I don't need to do anything."</h2>

  <p>A class action is appropriate for low-value-per-claimant harms that do not justify individual litigation. For personal injury, your individual claim is almost always worth more than a class share. If you are notified of a class action involving a product that injured you, read the notice carefully: most class actions allow you to opt out and pursue your individual injury claim. If you do not opt out, you give up the right to bring an individual case.</p>

  <h2>Myth 10: "If the company is overseas, I can't sue them."</h2>

  <p>You can usually sue a foreign manufacturer that distributes products into the United States. The "stream of commerce" doctrine establishes personal jurisdiction in U.S. courts where the manufacturer's products reach consumers. The procedure is harder (Hague Convention service, ancillary collection proceedings) but the case is viable. Plaintiffs' counsel usually also sue the U.S. subsidiary, U.S. distributor, and U.S. retailer to simplify collection.</p>

  <h2>Myth 11: "I have to pay the lawyer up front."</h2>

  <p>Virtually no product liability case is taken on an hourly basis. The standard is contingency: the lawyer takes a percentage of the recovery (typically one-third pre-suit, 40% in suit/trial), advances all case expenses, and absorbs the loss if the case is unsuccessful. Initial consultations are free. The contingency model is what makes product cases accessible to ordinary consumers. If a "product liability lawyer" wants you to pay up front, they are not a real product liability lawyer.</p>

  <h2>Myth 12: "Expert witnesses are paid to say whatever the lawyer wants."</h2>

  <p>The defense bar uses this line in voir dire often. The reality: courts have built layered systems to control expert testimony. Federal Rule of Evidence 702 and the Daubert standard require experts to use reliable methodology applied reliably to the facts of the case. Trial courts hold "Daubert hearings" to gatekeep expert testimony. Experts whose methodology is unreliable are excluded. Experts who repeatedly testify for one side beyond the bounds of their actual expertise are impeached by their own prior testimony. The system is not perfect but it is not "say whatever the lawyer wants."</p>

  <h2>Myth 13: "Punitive damages are a windfall to plaintiffs."</h2>

  <p>Punitive damages serve a specific public purpose: to deter manufacturers from gross negligence or intentional concealment of known defects. Without punitives, a manufacturer that knows a product is dangerous can rationally decide that paying compensatory damages to the injured is cheaper than redesigning the product. The Ford Pinto memo is the classic example: Ford literally calculated that paying out a few hundred wrongful-death claims was cheaper than the $11/unit fuel-tank fix. Punitive damages flip that calculation. The "windfall" framing assumes the alternative is fair; the alternative is that profitable defect-concealment becomes a sustainable business strategy.</p>

  <h2>Myth 14: "Settlement means the manufacturer admits the product is defective."</h2>

  <p>No. Settlements are virtually always concluded with explicit no-admission-of-liability clauses. The manufacturer pays without conceding any factual or legal point. Settlement reflects a risk-and-cost calculation, not an admission. This is one reason individual settlements are often confidential &mdash; the manufacturer wants to avoid setting a settlement-value benchmark for similar cases.</p>

  <h2>Myth 15: "Product liability lawsuits drive up consumer prices and hurt the economy."</h2>

  <p>This is the central tort-reform talking point. Empirical research (RAND Institute for Civil Justice; American Bar Foundation studies) consistently finds that the cost of the tort system, including all product liability cases, is a small fraction of overall U.S. economic activity, and is far outweighed by the safety improvements driven by liability exposure: the child-resistant pill bottle, the airbag, the rollover-resistant SUV design, the redesigned crib slats, the fire-retardant pajama, the recalled lead-paint toy. The economic case against the product-liability system depends on ignoring its primary product: safer products. The Ford Pinto fuel tank, the side-saddle GM pickup, and the Bridgestone-Firestone Wilderness AT tire all changed because of litigation, not because of regulation.</p>

